Buffalo Bore is introducing a truly Heavy 30-30 Winchester loading. This new load utilizes a 190gr. custom Hawk bullet and gives the venerable 30-30 here-to-for unrealized power and is designed so that the person who owns a 30-30 can now reliably kill elk or moose sized game. The 30-30 can now be carried as a defensive tool in grizzly country and will be much more effective in stopping a grizzly attack than any other 30-30 ammunition in the world. This heavy 30-30 load is not designed for deer, although it will kill deer and if you line them up right, it will kill three or four deer with one shot……….

The custom 190gr. hawk bullet is designed with a harder core and thicker than normal jacket, so the expansion is minimal, thus insuring very deep penetration which is needed to break large bones and destroy organs deep inside large game animals. This load generates an unreal 2100 fps from normal 20 inch carbines—this is the type of velocity that the ordinary 170gr. 30-30 loads generate, but again, we are using a 190gr. bullet. The product SKU# for this load is 28A/20
Check the below real world velocities from my personal stock, over-the-counter firearms—truly amazing.
2071 fps -- Marlin Model 336 20 inch saddle ring carbine circa 1950’s
2061 fps -- Win. Model 94 20 inch carbine circa 1980’s

2146 fps -- Win. Model 94 20 inch carbine circa 1980’s
2020 fps -- Win. Model 94AE 16 inch Trapper carbine circa 1992
1983 fps -- Savage 99 26 inch rifle circa 1917 - Not a Typo
Note that the longest barrel gave the slowest velocity and even the short 16 inch Winchester trapper model gives faster speeds than the 26 inch Savage 99 rifle, which shows that barrel length is not always the sole indicator of velocities a firearm will generate.
Buffalo Bore always uses stock over-the-counter- firearms that give real world velocities. Other ammunition companies normally use laboratory test barrels which give much higher velocities than stock firearms. We at Buffalo Bore see this long established practice as misleading to the consumer.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Caracal F QS Rare Waffen Werks Stamped 7 clips 9mm
postcontent:
Selling my Caracal F QS.  It's one of the original Waffen Werks stamped from when they were importing through Tennessee.  Only 78 of these models were produced with the WW stamp and my weapon was procured directly from Keith at Waffen.  Comes with 7 clips (I might have 8, missing one somewhere), the quick loading tool for the clips, Caracal locking case and MFG brochure/manual.  It's a very nice and complete set. It's seen very light duty at the range due to the current scarcity of ammunition.

Look around only and you will see it's almost impossible to find one of the original Caracal imports and when I spoke with the new distributor they said all the original WW stamped were being collected for service, melted down and replaced by a brand new weapon.  Those who wanted to keep the WW stamped edition and just have the existing gun serviced have to wait till September 2013.  When I asked the rep said she'd estimate over 50 WW Fs had been received and melted down so its unclear now many of these are still in existence.  

Now that Caracal has hired JJ Racaza as their spokesman and the new lines are launching later this year with a big marketing push, the collectability (and price) of these ultra rare editions will only increase from here. 

Sources:
http://www.caracalforum.com/viewtopic.php?f=9&t=375

title: For Sale:  Remington Model 11 'The Sportsman'
location: Smithfield, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
This is a 1936 Remington Model 11 in great condition. It is 'The Sportsman'. The poly choke was built with the gun in 1936...it is not an add on. It is Full, Modified and Improved Cylinder. Wood is great. The bluing has wear but no pitting or rust. A great classical hunting gun. This gun is the clone of the Browning A5. I have more pics to email if you wish. The Remington Model 11 was not made either by or for Browning. It was manufactured by Remington, under designs patented by Browning. The same is true of the 'Browning' Auto-5 produced in Belgium (by Fabrique Nationale) and Japan (by Miroku).

John Moses Browning had licensed exclusive world manufacturing and sales rights, with an arrangement for royalties to be paid to him, for his Automatic Shotgun to F.N. in 1902.

John M. Browning negotiated with F.N. to cede to Remington the U.S. manufacture and sales rights, resulting in the introduction of the Remington Autoloading Shotgun in 1905. The F.N. and Remington guns were practically identical, with many parts being interchangeable.

Prior to America's entry into WWII, when F.N.'s production facilities fell into the hands of the advancing German army, Remington produced a version which was marked "Browning Arms Company, St. Louis, Missouri", which remained in limited production until after the liberation and rebuilding of the F.N. facilities following the war.

title: For Sale:  1878 Torre Annunziata Vetterli 6.5mm Carcano
postcontent:
One of the rarer Vetterlis from the Torre Annunziata armory.  Made in 1878 and converted to 6.5mm in WW1.  This rifle is in excellent condition considering its age.  The barrel and receiver retain 90+% of bluing while the lower housing is at 60-70%.  The bore is amazing (sorry, couldn't get a clear picture).  There are NO import marks on this rifle.

I have not fired this rifle but it appears to be 100% in working order with an excellent trigger, strong mainspring, and all around nice action.  The cleaning rod is slightly bent and doesn't always want to screw in on the first try.

PLEASE NOTE: Firing this rifle with modern, full strength ammunition is NOT reccommended. With other rifles of this type there have been instances of gas and particles being blown back into the face of the shooter when using full strength ammo.  Other owners have reported that these rifles function just fine with reduced-load rounds so I suggest that if you do want to shoot this rifle, you have a reloader remove some of the powder from modern 6.5 Carcano ammo (Hornaday, PRVI, etc.)

This rifle is an antique so it may be shipped directly to the buyer. Shipping charges will be extra and determined after purchase. DEAR SCAMMERS: DON'T BOTHER. I WILL NOT BE SENDING YOU OR ANYONE ELSE MONEY FROM AN OVERPAYMENT!

I accept checks, cach, and money orders.  Checks must be given a couple of business days to clear.  Thanks for looking.
